<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-autonomous-odes" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Autonomous Differential Equations</title>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       INTRO PROSE
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <p>
    Look back at the two population models we have been working with:
    <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = 4P(5-P)</m> and <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = -2P(10-P)</m>.
    Notice that in both cases, the right-hand side only involves <m>P</m>, and there
    is no <m>t</m> anywhere. 
    When the rate of change depends only on the current state and not on time itself,
    the long-term behavior of solutions is much more predictable and structured.
    We refer to such equations as <em>autonomous ODEs</em>.
  </p>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       DEFINITION: AUTONOMOUS ODE
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <definition xml:id="def-autonomous-ode">
    <title>Autonomous First-Order Differential Equation</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A <term>first-order autonomous differential equation</term> is one of the form
        <me>\frac{dy}{dt} = f(y),</me>
        where the right-hand side depends only on <m>y</m> and not explicitly on <m>t</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    For example, <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = 2P(P-10)</m> and <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = 2P(10-P)</m>
    are both autonomous, since the right-hand side involves only <m>P</m>.
    On the other hand, <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt} = yt^2</m> is <em>not</em> autonomous,
    since <m>t</m> appears explicitly on the right-hand side.
  </p>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       CHECKPOINT
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <exercise xml:id="ex-mc-autonomous">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Select all of the following that are first-order autonomous differential equations.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="no">
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p><m>\dfrac{dy}{dt} = y^3 - 2y</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Correct! The right-hand side depends only on <m>y</m>.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p><m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = 3P(P-5)</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Correct! The right-hand side depends only on <m>P</m>.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p><m>\dfrac{dy}{dt} = y^2\sin(y)</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Correct! Even though <m>\sin(y)</m> is a complicated function, it depends only on <m>y</m>, not on <m>t</m>.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p><m>\dfrac{dy}{dt} = yt^2</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Not autonomous. The right-hand side involves <m>t</m> explicitly,
            so this does not fit the form <m>dy/dt = f(y)</m>.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      
    </choices>
  </exercise>
<observation xml:id="obs-equilibrium-autonomous">
  <title>Equilibrium Solutions to Autonomous DEs</title>
  <p>
    The equilibrium solutions to <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt} = f(y)</m> occur when <m>f(y) = 0</m>.
  </p>
</observation>

<p>
  For example, the equilibrium solutions to <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = 2P(P-10)</m> are found
  by solving <m>2P(P-10) = 0</m>, giving <m>P = 0</m> and <m>P = 10</m>.
</p>

<solution>
  <title>Why this is true</title>
  <p>
    An equilibrium solution is a constant function <m>y(t) = C</m>. Since <m>y</m> is
    constant, <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt} = 0</m>. Plugging into the ODE gives
    <me>0 = f(C),</me>
    so <m>C</m> must be a zero of <m>f</m>. Conversely, if <m>f(C) = 0</m> then
    <m>y(t) = C</m> satisfies the ODE since both sides equal zero.
  </p>
</solution>

<exercise xml:id="ex-mc-equilibrium-autonomous">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find all equilibrium solutions to <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt} = (y-2)^2</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <choices randomize="no">
    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = 0</m> and <m>y = 2</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Not quite. Set <m>f(y) = (y-2)^2 = 0</m> and solve. Remember
          <m>(y-2)^2 = 0</m> only when <m>y - 2 = 0</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>y = 2</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct! Setting <m>(y-2)^2 = 0</m> gives <m>y = 2</m> as the only equilibrium solution.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = 0</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Not quite. Plug <m>y = 0</m> into <m>(y-2)^2</m>: you get
          <m>(0-2)^2 = 4 \neq 0</m>, so <m>y = 0</m> is not an equilibrium.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice>
      <statement><p>There are no equilibrium solutions.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Not quite. Set <m>(y-2)^2 = 0</m> and solve for <m>y</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
  </choices>
</exercise>
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       EXISTENCE AND UNIQUENESS
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

 
 

